25|$|The {{capacity}} to lie {{has also been}} claimed to be possessed by non-humans in language studies with great apes. In one instance, gorilla Koko, when asked who tore a sink from the wall, pointed {{to one of her}} handlers and <b>then</b> <b>laughed.</b> Deceptive body language, such as feints that mislead as to the intended direction of attack or flight, is observed in many species including wolves. A mother bird deceives when it pretends to have a broken wing to divert the attention of a perceived predator– including unwitting humans– from the eggs in its nest to itself, most notably the killdeer.|$|E
